subsection.p:
Let \mathbf F=(P,Q,R) be a vector field in space. Its flux 2-form is \boxed{\Phi_{\mathbf F} = P\,dy\wedge dz + Q\,dz\wedge dx + R\,dx\wedge dy.} Taking the exterior derivative gives
d\Phi_{\mathbf F} \amp= dP\wedge dy\wedge dz + dQ\wedge dz\wedge dx + dR\wedge dx\wedge dy \amp= P_x\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz \amp\quad+ Q_y\,dy\wedge dz\wedge dx \amp\quad+ R_z\,dz\wedge dx\wedge dy \amp= (P_x+Q_y+R_z)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz.
The coefficient is the divergence: \boxed{\nabla\cdot\mathbf F=P_x+Q_y+R_z.} So \boxed{d\Phi_{\mathbf F} = (\nabla\cdot\mathbf F)\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz.}

Let E be the ball of radius a centered at the origin: x^2+y^2+z^2\le a^2. Let \mathbf F=(x,y,z), with flux form \Phi=x\,dy\wedge dz+y\,dz\wedge dx+z\,dx\wedge dy. As above, d\Phi=3\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz. Therefore
\int_{\partial E}\Phi \amp= \int_E d\Phi \amp= \int_E 3\,dx\wedge dy\wedge dz \amp= 3\operatorname{Volume}(E) \amp= 3\left(\frac43\pi a^3\right) \amp= 4\pi a^3.
So \boxed{\iint_{\partial E}(x,y,z)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}_{\mathrm{out}}\,dS = 4\pi a^3.}

paragraphs.p:
Now integrate over the sphere S_a of radius a, oriented outward. On the sphere, \widehat{\mathbf n}_{\mathrm{out}}=\frac{(x,y,z)}{a}, and \mathbf G=\frac{(x,y,z)}{a^3}. Thus
\mathbf G\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}_{\mathrm{out}} \amp= \frac{(x,y,z)}{a^3}\cdot\frac{(x,y,z)}{a} \amp= \frac{x^2+y^2+z^2}{a^4} \amp= \frac1{a^2}.
Therefore \boxed{\int_{S_a}\Psi = \iint_{S_a}\mathbf G\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}_{\mathrm{out}}\,dS = \frac1{a^2}(4\pi a^2) = 4\pi.}

subsection.p:
This is the geometric meaning of
\boxed{\partial(\partial E)=\emptyset.}
A boundary has no boundary.

In vector language, this says:
\boxed{\iint_{\partial E}(\nabla\times\mathbf F)\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}_{\mathrm{out}}\,dS=0,}
as long as \mathbf F is defined on a region containing E.
